ame=\"NDB-Ferdinand II\">{{NDB|5|83|85|Ferdinand II.|Eder, Karl|118532510}}</ref><ref group=lower-roman name=\"BLKO-Margaretha\">{{BLKO |wstitle=Habsburg, Margaretha (K\u00f6nigin von Spanien) |volume=7 |page=13}}</ref><br/>{{smaller|{{nowrap|1540\u201390}}}}|AnnA2=[[Anna of Austria, Queen of Spain|'''Anna'''<br/>of Austria]]<ref group=lower-roman name=\"BLKO-Philip III\"/><br/>{{smaller|{{nowrap|1549\u201380}}}}| MarB1=[[Maria Anna of Bavaria (1551\u20131608)|'''Maria Anna'''<br/>of Bavaria]]<ref group=lower-roman name=\"NDB-Ferdinand II\"/><ref group=lower-roman name=\"BLKO-Margaretha\"/><br/>{{smaller|{{nowrap|1551\u20131608}}}}| Will5=[[William V, Duke of Bavaria|'''William&nbsp;V'''<br />Duke of Bavaria]]<ref group=lower-roman name=\"BLKO-Maria Anna von Bayern\">{{BLKO|wstitle=Habsburg, Maria Anna von Bayern|volume=7 |page=23}}</ref><br/>{{smaller|{{nowrap|1548\u20131626}}}}| RenLo=[[Renata of Lorraine|'''Renata'''<br/>of Lorraine]]<ref group=lower-roman name=\"BLKO-Maria Anna von Bayern\"/><br/>{{smaller|{{nowrap|1544\u20131602}}}}}}\n{{chart|boxstyle=border-width:1px;border-radius: 0.5em| | | | | | |!| | | | | | | | | | |!| | | | | | | |}}\n{{chart|boxstyle=border-width:1px;border-radius: 0.5em| | | | | |Phil3|~|~|~|~|~|~|~|~|MarA1| | | Phil3=[[Philip III of Spain|'''Philip&nbsp;III'''<br/>King of Spain]]<ref group=lower-roman name=\"BLKO-Maria Anna von Spanien\">{{BLKO |wstitle=Habsburg, Maria Anna von Spanien |volume=7 |page=23}}</ref><ref group=lower-roman name=\"BLKO-Philipp IV\">{{BLKO |wstitle=Habsburg, Philipp IV. |volume=7 |page=122}}</ref><br/>{{smaller|{{nowrap|1578\u20131621}}}}| MarA1=[[Margaret of Austria, Queen of Spain|'''Margaret'''<br/>of Austria]]<ref group=lower-roman name=\"BLKO-Maria Anna von Spanien\"/><ref group=lower-roman name=\"BLKO-Philipp IV\"/><br/>{{smaller|{{nowrap|1584\u20131611}}}}| Ferd2=[[Ferdinand II, Holy Roman Emperor|'''Ferdinand&nbsp;II'''<br/>Holy Roman Emperor]]<ref group=lower-roman name=\"BLKO-Mariana\"/><br/>{{smaller|{{nowrap|1578\u20131637}}}}| MarB2=[[Maria Anna of Bavaria (1574\u20131616)|'''Maria Anna'''<br/>of Bavaria]]<ref group=lower-roman name=\"BLKO-Mariana\"/><br/>{{smaller|{{nowrap|1574\u20131616}}}}}}\n{{chart/end}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|'''Notes:'''\n{{notelist-lr}}<!--- use either {{Efn-lr}} and/or <ref group=lower-roman /> To fill this notelist -->\n{{chart bottom}}\n\n==Family==\nPhilip married [[Margaret of Austria (1584-1611)|Margaret of Austria]], his second cousin. They had the following children:\n\n*[[Anne of Austria|Anne]] (22 September 1601 \u2013 20 January 1666), queen of France\n*Maria (1 February 1603 \u2013 2 February 1603)\n*[[Philip IV of Spain]] (8 April 1605 \u2013 17 September 1665)\n*[[Maria Anna of Spain|Maria Anna]] (18 August 1606 \u2013 13 May 1646), empress of the Holy Roman Empire\n*[[Archduke Charles of Austria (1607\u20131632)|Charles]] (14 September 1607 \u2013 30 July 1632)\n*[[Cardinal-Infante Ferdinand of Austria|Ferdinand]] (16 May 1609 \u2013 9 November 1641), a cardinal and military commander\n*Margaret Frances (24 May 1610 \u2013 11 March 1617)\n*Alphonse Maurice (22 September 1611 \u2013 16 September 1612)\n\n==See also==\n*[[Palacio de la Ribera]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*Cipolla, Carlo M. (ed) ''The Fontana Economic History of Europe: The Sixteenth and Seventeenth Centuries.'' London: Fontana. (1974)\n*Cruz, Anne J. ''Discourses of Poverty: Social Reform and the Picaresque Novel.'' Toronto: University of Toronto Press. (1999)\n*Davenport, Frances G. ''European Treaties Bearing on the History of the United States and Its Dependencies.'' The Lawbook Exchange, Ltd. (2004)\n*Elliott, J. H. ''Imperial Spain: 1469\u20131716.'' London: Penguin. (1963)\n*Feros, Antionio. ''Kingship and Favouritism in the Spain of Philip III, 1598\u20131621.'' Cambridge: Cambridge University Press. (2006)\n*Goodman, David. ''Spanish Naval Power, 1589\u20131665: Reconstruction and Defeat.'' Cambridge: Cambridge University Press. (2002)\n*Kamen, Henry. ''Spain, 1469\u20131714: A Society of Conflict.'' Harlow: Pearson Education. (2005)\n*Harvey, Leonard Patrick. ''Muslims in Spain, 1500\u20131614.'' Chicago: University of Chicago Press. (2005)\n*Hoffman, Philip T. and Kathyrn Norberg (eds). ''Fiscal Crises, Liberty, and Representative Government 1450\u20131789.'' Stanford: Stanford University Press. (2001)\n*De Maddalena, Aldo. ''Rural Europe, 1500\u20131750.'' in Cipolla (ed) 1974.\n*Mattingly, Garrett. ''The Armada.'' New York: Mariner Books. (2005)\n*Munck, Thomas. ''Seventeenth Century Europe, 1598\u20131700.'' London: Macmillan. (1990)\n*Parker, Geoffrey. ''Europe in Crisis, 1598\u20131648.'' London: Fontana. (1984)\n*Parker, Geoffrey. ''The Dutch Revolt.'' London: Pelican Books. (1985)\n*Parker, Geoffrey. ''The Army of Flanders and the Spanish Road, 1567\u20131659.'' Cambridge: Cambridge University Press. (2004)\n*Perry, Mary Elizabeth. ''The Handless Maiden: Moriscos and the politics of religion in early modern Spain.'' Princeton: Princeton University Press. (2005)\n*Polisensky, J. V. ''The Thirty Years War.'' London: NEL. (1971)\n*Ringrose, David. ''Spain, Europe and the \"Spanish Miracle\", 1700\u20131900.'' Cambridge: Cambridge University Press. (1998)\n*S\u00e1nchez, Magdalena S. ''Pious and Political Images of a Habsburg Woman at the Court of Philip III (1598\u20131621).'' in S\u00e1nchez and Saint-Sa\u00ebns (eds) 1996.\n*S\u00e1nchez, Magdalena S. and Alain Saint-Sa\u00ebns (eds). ''Spanish women in the golden age: images and realities.'' Greenwood Publishing Group. (1996)\n*Stradling, R. A. ''Philip IV and the Government of Spain, 1621\u20131665.'' Cambridge: Cambridge University Press. (1988)\n*Thompson, I. A. A. ''Castile, Constitionalism and Liberty.'' in Hoffman and Norburg (eds) 2001.\n*Wedgwood, C. V. ''The Thirty Years War.'' London: Methuen. (1981)\n*Williams, Patrick. ''The Great Favourite: the Duke of Lerma and the court and government of Philip III of Spain, 1598\u20131621.'' Manchester: Manchester University Press. (2006)\n*Zagorin, Perez. ''Rebels and Rulers, 1500\u20131660. Volume II: Provincial rebellion: Revolutionary civil wars, 1560\u20131660.'' Cambridge: Cambridge University Press. (1992)\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Commons category|Philip III of Spain}}\n*{{EB1911|wstitle = Philip III., king of Spain|volume=21}}\n*See also Paul C. Allen, ''Philip III and the Pax Hispanica: The Failure of Grand Strategy'' (Yale UP: 2000) for an extensive discussion of the foreign policy of Philip III. Allen's is a revisionist work that also argues for a greater role played in international affairs by the Council of State and its leaders in this period rather than by Lerma.\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou|[[Habsburg Spain|House of Habsburg]]|14 April|1578|31 March|1621}}\n{{s-reg}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Philip II of Spain]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[King of Spain]] and [[King of Portugal|Portugal]];<br>[[List of monarchs of Sardinia|King of Sardinia]], [[List of monarchs of Naples|Naples]] and [[List of monarchs of Sicily|Sicily]]; <br>[[Duke of Milan]]|years=1598\u20131621}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Philip IV of Spain]]}}\n|-\n{{s-roy|es}}\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[Diego, Prince of Asturias|Diego]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prince of Asturias]] | years=1582\u201398}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Philip IV of Spain|Philip]] }}\n{{s-ttl |title=[[Prince of Portugal]]| years=1582\u201398}}\n{{s-aft |after=[[Anne of Austria|Anne]] }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Monarchs of Spain}}\n{{Spanish Empire}}\n{{Monarchs of Portugal}}\n{{Infantes of Spain}}\n{{Portuguese infantes}}\n{{Princes of Asturias}}\n{{Austrian archdukes}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Philip 03 Of Spain}}\n[[Category:Philippine dynasty]]\n[[Category:1578 births]]\n[[Category:1621 deaths]]\n[[Category:16th-century Spanish monarchs]]\n[[Category:17th-century Spanish monarchs]]\n[[Category:16th-century Portuguese monarchs]]\n[[Category:17th-century Portuguese monarchs]]\n[[Category:16th-century Castilian monarchs]]\n[[Category:17th-century Castilian monarchs]]\n[[Category:16th-century Aragonese monarchs]]\n[[Category:17th-century Aragonese monarchs]]\n[[Category:16th-century Kings of Sicily]]\n[[Category:17th-century Kings of Sicily]]\n[[Category:Spanish Baroque people]]\n[[Category:Spanish people of the Eighty Years' War]]\n[[Category:People of the Anglo-Spanish War (1585\u20131604)]]\n[[Category:Nobility from Madrid]]\n[[Category:Kings of Sicily]]\n[[Category:Princes of Asturias]]\n[[Category:Dukes of Montblanc]]\n[[Category:Princes of Portugal]]\n[[Category:Spanish infantes]]\n[[Category:Portuguese infantes]]\n[[Category:Dukes of Milan]]\n[[Category:Knights of Santiago]]\n[[Category:Knights of the Golden Fleece]]\n[[Category:Burials in the Pantheon of Kings at El Escorial]]\n[[Category:Grand Masters of the Order of the Golden Fleece]]\n[[Category:16th-century Spanish people]]\n[[Category:17th-century Spanish people]]\n", "name_user": "64.237.234.97", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eEarly life)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philip_III_of_Spain"}
{"title_page": "Gajendra Chauhan", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian actor}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Gajendra Chauhan\n| image       = \n| Home        = Patel nagar west \n                Shadi khampur old \n                Ranjit Nagar.\nGajendra_Chauhan_at_the_Dadasaheb_Phalke_Academy_Awards_2010.jpg\n| imagesize   = \n| caption     = Gajendra Chauhan in 2010\n| birth_name  =  \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1956|10|10}}\n| birth_place = [[Delhi]], [[India]]\n| nationality = Indian\n| other_names = Gajendra Singh Chauhan\n| occupation  = {{unbulleted list|[[Actor]]| \nChairman of [[Film and Television Institute of India|FTII]] : 09 June 2015 - 11 October 2017}}\nSucceeded by [[Anupam Kher]]\n| years active= 1984-present \n}}\n\n'''Gajendra Singh Chauhan''' (born 10 October 1956), known professionally as '''Gajendra Chauhan''', is an actor known for his work on Indian television, especially his portrayal of [[Yudhishthira]] in the historical television series ''[[Mahabharat (1988 TV series)|Mahabharat]]'' (1988\u201390). He has also had significant roles in a few [[B movie]]s, and a larger number of [[cameo appearance]]s in other films. In 2015, he was appointed chairman of the [[Film and Television Institute of India]] (FTII), which sparked controversy and opposition by FTII students, leading to his resignation in October 2017.\n\n==Early life==\nChauhan was born in Delhi.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gajendra Chauhan Biography|url=https://www.filmcentro.com/profile/gajendra-chauhan-biography|website=www.filmcentro.com|publisher=Filmcentro - Actors & Actress profile|accessdate=12 July 2015}}</ref> He did a diploma in radiography from [[All India Institute of Medical Sciences]] (AIIMS) before he moved to Mumbai to pursue a career in acting.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gajendra Chauhan has political clout, but no star power|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/specials/gajendra-chauhan-has-political-clout-but-no-star-power-115061800578_1.html|website=business-standard.com|publisher=Business Standard|date=20 June 2015|accessdate=13 July 2015}}</ref> There he studied acting in the school run by Roshan Taneja, who had previously taught at FTII.<ref name=\"HT Interview\">{{cite web|last1=Ghosh|first1=Paramita|title=My favourite film is 3 Idiots: Gajendra Chauhan, FTII chairman|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/my-favourite-film-is-3-idiots-gajendra-chauhan-ftii-chairman/article1-1360564.aspx|website=hindustantimes.com|publisher=Hundustan Times|accessdate=12 July 2015|date=20 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Acting career==\nChauhan's acting career spans 34 years, and by his own count, he has worked in 600 [[television series]] and almost 150 movies during that period.<ref name=\"IE June 18, 2015\">{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/interview-my-credentials-arent-bad-let-me-perform-says-gajendra-chauhan/|title=\u2018I don\u2019t believe my credentials are bad\u2026Let me perform,\u2019 says Gajendra Chauhan|date=18 June 2015|work=The Indian Express}}</ref><ref name=\"indiatimes.com\">{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/hindi/Im-600-serials-old-now-Gajendra-Chauhan/articleshow/11765192.cms|title=I\u2019m 600 serials old now: Gajendra Chauhan|work=The Times of India}}</ref> His first break as an actor was in television series ''Paying Guest'' in 1983, and he went on to act in shows such as ''Rajni'', ''Air Hostess'' and ''Adalat''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1150621/jsp/7days/story_26882.jsp|title='No one wants an ordinary man to occupy a big position'|date=21 June 2015|accessdate=6 August 2015|newspaper=The Telegraph}}</ref> The first acting part in a film that he did was in ''Main Chup Nahi Rahoongi'' in 1986.<ref name=\"HT Interview\"/> In reviews of his film career, ''[[Times of India]]'' and ''[[Firstpost]]'' wrote that he had played significant roles only in a few \"[[B movie#C movie|C-grade]]\" movies, with most of his other roles being [[cameo appearances]], a few of which were in mainstream movie.<ref name=\"TOI Jul 11 2015\">{{citation|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Gajendra-Chauhan-A-34-year-veteran-of-C-grade-exploits/articleshow/48026077.cms| title=Gajendra Chauhan: A 34-year veteran of C-grade exploits|accessdate=13 July 2015|work=[[Times of India]]|date=11 July 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"FP 17Jun2015\">{{cite news|last1=Ramakrishnan|first1=Swetha|title=A career in forgettable cameos: Here is FTII chairman Gajendra Chauhan's filmography|work=[[Firstpost]]|date=17 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Mahabharat ===\n{{Further|Mahabharat (1988 TV series)}}\nChauhan was initially offered to play the role of Lord [[Krishna]] in the television series, and shot for two episodes of the series in this role.<ref name=\"Times of India\">{{cite web|last1=Sharma|first1=Suruchi|title=I'm 600 series old now: Gajendra Chauhan|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/hindi/Im-600-serials-old-now-Gajendra-Chauhan/articleshow/11765192.cms|website=timesofindia.com|publisher=[[The Times of India]]|accessdate=12 July 2015|date=6 February 2012}}</ref> However filming for the first series was delayed, and Chauhan moved south to take on new work.<ref name=\"Times of India\"/> Upon his return, Chauhan had put on weight and was considered unsuitable for the role of Krishna. He was later offered the role of [[Yudhishthira]], which went on to being the role he has become better known by.<ref name=\"Times of India\"/>\n\n==Administration and politics==\nChauhan has also been involved in the administration of ''Cinema and Television Artists Association'' for 20 years, and served as its president for a year.<ref name=\"IE June 18, 2015\" /><ref name=\"rediff.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/yes-i-have-done-adult-films-but-nobody-is-talking-about-my-good-films/20150630.htm|title='Yes, I have done adult films. But nobody is talking about my good films'|date=30 June 2015|accessdate=12 July 2015|website=rediff.com|publisher=Rediff Movies}}</ref> In 2004 Chauhan entered politics,<ref name=indiatimes.com /> and became a member of the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] (BJP), for which he has worked as the national convener for culture.<ref name=\"IE June 18, 2015\" /><ref name=NDTV>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/protests-at-film-institute-in-pune-after-actor-bjp-member-gajendra-chauhan-is-appointed-chief-771313|title=Protests at Film Institute in Pune After Actor-BJP Member Gajendra Chauhan is Appointed Chief|date=13 June 2015|accessdate=12 July 2015|website=ndtv.com|publisher=NDTV}}</ref>\n\n===Chairman of Film and Television Institute of India===\n{{Further|Film and Television Institute of India}}\nOn 9 June 2015, Chauhan was appointed as the Chairman of the [[Film and Television Institute of India]] (FTII).<ref name=\"FTII appointment\">{{cite web|last1=Joshi|first1=Yogesh|title=Mahabharat actor as FTII prez sparks students' protest over BJP link|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/mumbai/ftii-students-say-protests-to-continue-against-appointment-of-new-chairperson/article1-1358025.aspx|website=hindustantimes.com|publisher=[[Hindustan Times]]|accessdate=12 July 2015|date=13 June 2015}}</ref> His appointment proved to be controversial amid allegations by students that it was a blatant attempt to \"[[saffronization|saffronize]] the institute\".<ref name=\"FTII appointment\"/> A section of left-wing students association, including [[All India Students Association]] (AISA) (the student wing of the [[Communist Party of India (Marxist\u2013Leninist) Liberation]]) continue to agitate.<ref name=AISA>{{cite web|author1=ANI|title=AISA protests against Gajendra Chauhan's appointment as FTII chief|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ani/aisa-protests-against-gajendra-chauhan-s-appointment-as-ftii-chief-115061600309_1.html|website=business-standard.com|publisher=Business Standard|accessdate=12 July 2015|date=16 June 2015}}</ref> Chauhan requested the students to give him a year to prove himself, and insisted that he would be better than the previous chairpersons.<ref name=\"anujkumar\">{{cite web|last1=Kumar|first1=Anij|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/i-am-a-self-made-man/article7329869.ece|title=I am a self-made man|website=thehindu.com|publisher=The Hundu|accessdate=12 July 2015|date=18 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nAmong those who have supported Chauhan's appointment as FTII chairman are BJP supporters and politicians including [[Mukesh Khanna]],<ref>http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/pune/Students-willing-for-talks-ministry-still-backs-choice/articleshow/48011905.cms</ref>[[Shatrughan Sinha]], [[Paresh Rawal]], [[Hema Malini]], [[Rajyavardhan Singh Rathore]], and [[Paintal]].<ref name=\"rediff.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Rajyavardhan Singh Rathore defends Gajendra Chauhan's selection as FTII chief|url=http://www.mid-day.com/articles/rajyavardhan-singh-rathore-defends-gajendra-chauhans-selection-as-ftii-chief/16361159|website=mid-day.com|publisher=Mid-Day|accessdate=12 July 2015|date=11 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author1=PTI|title=Gajendra Chauhan chosen over icons as he could devote more time|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/gajendra-chauhan-chosen-over-icons-as-he-could-devote-more-time-government/|website=indianexpress.com|publisher=Indian Express|accessdate=12 July 2015|date=10 July 2015}}</ref> Many more including FTII alumni and former teachers, actors, film technicians, filmmakers and political leaders have opposed his appointment, prominent among whom include [[Ranbir Kapoor]], [[Kalki Koechlin]], [[Nawazuddin Siddiqui]], [[Anupam Kher]], [[Piyush Mishra]], [[Anand Patwardhan]], [[Kiran Rao]], [[Jahnu Barua]], [[Salman Khan]], [[Rishi Kapoor]],<ref>{{cite web|title=FTII row: Top Bollywood personalities join chorus against Gajendra Chauhan|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/ftii-row-top-bollywood-personalities-join-chorus-against-gajendra-chauhan/1/450384.html|website=indiatoday.com|publisher=India Today|accessdate=12 July 2015|date=9 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Venugopal|first1=Vasudha|title=Amitabh Bachchan could've been FTII chairman, but Modi govt ignored I&B list and selected Gajendra Chauhan|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/amitabh-bachchan-couldve-been-ftii-chairman-but-modi-govt-ignored-ib-list-and-selected-gajendra-chauhan/articleshow/48025768.cms|website=economictimes.com|publisher=The Economic Times|accessdate=12 July 2015|date=11 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=It is nothing to be happy or dissatisfied about: Jahnu Barua on Gajendra Chauhan's appointment as FTII chairman|url=http://www.ibnlive.com/news/movies/giving-gajendra-chauhan-a-chance-is-not-a-problem-jahnu-barua-on-ftii-stir-1005896.html|website=ibnlive.com|publisher=IBN Live|accessdate=12 July 2015|date=14 June 2015}}</ref> [[Resul Pookutty]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/resul-pookutty-on-ftii-controversy-gajendra-chauhan-cannot-inspire-students-777502|title=Resul Pookutty on FTII Controversy: Gajendra Chauhan Cannot Inspire Students|date=2 July 2015|accessdate=6 August 2015|publisher=NDTV}}</ref> [[Rajkummar Rao]], [[Amol Palekar]],<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/ftii-row-rajkummar-rao-amol-palekar-demand-chauhan-s-removal-115071100436_1.html|title=Rajkummar Rao, Amol Palekar demand Chauhan\u2019s removal|date=11 July 2015|accessdate=6 August 2015|newspaper=Business Standard}}</ref> [[Soumitra Chatterjee]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/gajendra-chauhan-who-veteran-actor-soumitra-chatterjee-backs-ftii-protests-1203303|title='Gajendra Chauhan Who?': Veteran Actor Soumitra Chatterjee Backs FTII Protests|date=3 August 2015|accessdate=6 August 2015|publisher=NDTV}}</ref> [[Rahul Gandhi]] and [[Arvind Kejriwal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-ftii-row-after-salman-khan-and-rahul-gandhi-arvind-kejriwal-speaks-up-against-gajendra-chauhan-2111317|title=After Salman Khan and Rahul Gandhi, Arvind Kejriwal speaks up against Gajendra Chauhan|date=5 August 2015|accessdate=6 August 2015|publisher=DNA}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"|Year\n! scope=\"col\"|Title\n! scope=\"col\"|Role\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\" | 1985\n| ''Main Chup Nahi Rahungi''\n|\n|-\n| ''Lallu Ram''\n| Sub Inspector\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''Jungle Love''\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\" | 1989\n| ''[[Khuli Khidki]]''\n| Avinash\n|-\n| ''Awara Zindagi''\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\" | 1991\n| ''Vasna''\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Dancer (1991 film)|Dancer]]''\n| Joshi\n|-\n| ''Jungle Ki Rani''\n|\n|-\n| ''Naagmani''\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\" | 1992\n| ''Jungle Ka Beta''\n|\n|-\n| ''Jawani Janeman''\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Dilwale Kabhi Na Hare]]''\n| Shibu\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''Mulaquat'' \n| Balraj\n|-\n|rowspan=\"8\" | 1994\n| ''Watan''\n|\n|-\n| ''Jai Maa Vaishno Devi''\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Pathreela Raasta]]'' \n|\n|-\n| ''[[Janam Se Pehle]]'' \n|\n|-\n| ''[[Vaade Iraade]]''\n|\n|-\n| ''Mohini''\n| Gandharv\n|-\n| ''Sone Ki Sita''\n|\n|-\n| [[Aao Pyaar Karen (1994 film)|Aao Pyaar Karen]]\n| Suraj\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\" | 1995\n| ''[[Ham Sab Chor Hain (1995 film)|Hum Sab Chor Hain]]''\n| Police Commissioner\n|-\n| ''Kaala Sach''\n|\n|-\n| ''Reshma''\n|\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[Himmatvar]]''\n| Inspector Patil\n|-\n|rowspan=\"6\" | 1997\n| ''Uff! Yeh Mohabbat''\n| Umang Usgaonkar\n|-\n| ''[[Vishwavidhaata]]''\n| Mukesh Mathur\n|-\n| ''[[Raja Ki Aayegi Baraat]]''\n| Pratap - Prosecutting attorney\n|-\n| ''[[Dharma Karma]]''\n| Police Inspector\n|-\n| ''[[Police Station]]''\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Bhayaanak Panja]]''\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\" | 1999\n| ''[[International Khiladi]]''\n| Rahul's Father \n|-\n| ''Inteqam Aurat Ka'' \n|\n|-\n| ''[[Hogi Pyaar Ki Jeet]]''\n| Arjun Singh \n|-\n| ''Dil Ka Sauda''\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\" | 2000\n| ''[[Billa No. 786]]''\n| Virendra Singh (Pinky's dad) \n|-\n| ''[[Aaj Ka Ravan]]''\n| ACP Rathod \n|-\n| ''Tapish''\n|\n|-\n| ''Saamri''\n|\n|-\n| ''Yeh Hai Prem Janjaal''\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\" | 2001\n| ''[[Rupa Rani Ramkali]]''\n|\n|-\n| ''Gumnam Hai Koi''\n| Vinod Kumar Tripathi \n|-\n| ''[[Arjun Devaa]]''\n| Virendra Choudhry \n|-\n| 2002\n| ''[[Tumko Na Bhool Paayenge]]''\n| Ex-Armyman \n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\" | 2003\n| ''[[Andaaz]]''\n| Mr. Sahay \n|-\n| ''[[Parwana (2003 film)|Parwana]]''\n| Ganesh fest dancer/singer \n|-\n| ''[[Baghban (2003 film)|Baghban]]''\n| Car salesman \n|-\n| 2004\n| ''Pati Ho To Aisa''\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\" | 2005\n| ''Dhadkanein''\n| Ravi Malhotra\n|-\n| ''[[Barsaat (2005 film)|Barsaat]]''\n| Arav's Father \n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Mere Jeevan Saathi (2006 film)|Mere Jeevan Saathi]]''\n| \n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Meri Doli Tere Angana]]''\n| Mahendra \n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Isi Life Mein]]''\n| Nareshchand\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Nakshatra (film)|Nakshatra]]''\n| Sharma \n|-\n|2013\n| ''[[Mahabharat Aur Barbareek|Mahabharat Aur Barbareek]]''\n| [[Yudhishthira|Yudhisthra]]\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Kahin Hai Mera Pyar]]'' \n| Priya's father\n|-\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"|Year\n! scope=\"col\"|Title\n! scope=\"col\"|Role\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''Sarrkkar: Risshton Ki Ankahi Kahani''\n|\n|\n|-\n| 1988\n| ''[[Mahabharat (1988 TV series)|Mahabharat]]''\n| Yudhishthira\n| 94 episodes between 2 October 1988 \u2013 24 June 1990\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''[[Kanoon (1993 TV series)|Kanoon]]''\n| Chandra Saxena\n| 14 episodes\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''The Zee Horror Show''\n| \n| \n|-\n| 2000\n| ''Noor Jahan''\n| \n| \n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[Aane Wala Pal]]''\n|\n|\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[Ramayan (2001-2002) TV Series]]''\n| [[Dasharath]]\n|\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Raavan (TV series)|Raavan]]''\n| Maharaj [[Dasharath]] (King of Ayodhya) \n|\n|-\n|2008-2009\n|''[[Naaginn (2007 TV series)|Naaginn]]''\n|Naagdev\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Shobha Somnath Ki]]''\n| \n| \n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Kya Hua Tera Vaada]]''\n| Mr. Chopra\n|\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Adaalat]]''\n| Colonel Desai\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Sankatmochan Mahabali Hanuman]]''\n| Sumant\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=1024111|name=Gajendra Chauhan}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chauhan, Gajendra}}\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:Indian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Indian male television actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Delhi]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian actor}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Gajendra Chauhan\n| image       = Gajendra_Chauhan_at_the_Dadasaheb_Phalke_Academy_Awards_2010.jpg\n| imagesize   = \n| caption     = Gajendra Chauhan in 2010\n| birth_name  =  \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1956|10|10}}\n| birth_place = [[Delhi]], [[India]]\n| nationality = Indian\n| other_names = Gajendra Singh Chauhan\n| occupation  = {{unbulleted list|[[Actor]]| \nChairman of [[Film and Television Institute of India|FTII]] : 09 June 2015 - 11 October 2017}}\nSucceeded by [[Anupam Kher]]\n| years active= 1984-present \n}}\n\n'''Gajendra Singh Chauhan''' (born 10 October 1956), known professionally as '''Gajendra Chauhan''', is an actor known for his work on Indian television, especially his portrayal of [[Yudhishthira]] in the historical television series ''[[Mahabharat (1988 TV series)|Mahabharat]]'' (1988\u201390). He has also had significant roles in a few [[B movie]]s, and a larger number of [[cameo appearance]]s in other films. In 2015, he was appointed chairman of the [[Film and Television Institute of India]] (FTII), which sparked controversy and opposition by FTII students, leading to his resignation in October 2017.\n\n==Early life==\nChauhan was born in Delhi.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gajendra Chauhan Biography|url=https://www.filmcentro.com/profile/gajendra-chauhan-biography|website=www.filmcentro.com|publisher=Filmcentro - Actors & Actress profile|accessdate=12 July 2015}}</ref> He did a diploma in radiography from [[All India Institute of Medical Sciences]] (AIIMS) before he moved to Mumbai to pursue a career in acting.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gajendra Chauhan has political clout, but no star power|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/specials/gajendra-chauhan-has-political-clout-but-no-star-power-115061800578_1.html|website=business-standard.com|publisher=Business Standard|date=20 June 2015|accessdate=13 July 2015}}</ref> There he studied acting in the school run by Roshan Taneja, who had previously taught at FTII.<ref name=\"HT Interview\">{{cite web|last1=Ghosh|first1=Paramita|title=My favourite film is 3 Idiots: Gajendra Chauhan, FTII chairman|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/my-favourite-film-is-3-idiots-gajendra-chauhan-ftii-chairman/article1-1360564.aspx|website=hindustantimes.com|publisher=Hundustan Times|accessdate=12 July 2015|date=20 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Acting career==\nChauhan's acting career spans 34 years, and by his own count, he has worked in 600 [[television series]] and almost 150 movies during that period.<ref name=\"IE June 18, 2015\">{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/interview-my-credentials-arent-bad-let-me-perform-says-gajendra-chauhan/|title=\u2018I don\u2019t believe my credentials are bad\u2026Let me perform,\u2019 says Gajendra Chauhan|date=18 June 2015|work=The Indian Express}}</ref><ref name=\"indiatimes.com\">{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/hindi/Im-600-serials-old-now-Gajendra-Chauhan/articleshow/11765192.cms|title=I\u2019m 600 serials old now: Gajendra Chauhan|work=The Times of India}}</ref> His first break as an actor was in television series ''Paying Guest'' in 1983, and he went on to act in shows such as ''Rajni'', ''Air Hostess'' and ''Adalat''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1150621/jsp/7days/story_26882.jsp|title='No one wants an ordinary man to occupy a big position'|date=21 June 2015|accessdate=6 August 2015|newspaper=The Telegraph}}</ref> The first acting part in a film that he did was in ''Main Chup Nahi Rahoongi'' in 1986.<ref name=\"HT Interview\"/> In reviews of his film career, ''[[Times of India]]'' and ''[[Firstpost]]'' wrote that he had played significant roles only in a few \"[[B movie#C movie|C-grade]]\" movies, with most of his other roles being [[cameo appearances]], a few of which were in mainstream movie.<ref name=\"TOI Jul 11 2015\">{{citation|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Gajendra-Chauhan-A-34-year-veteran-of-C-grade-exploits/articleshow/48026077.cms| title=Gajendra Chauhan: A 34-year veteran of C-grade exploits|accessdate=13 July 2015|work=[[Times of India]]|date=11 July 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"FP 17Jun2015\">{{cite news|last1=Ramakrishnan|first1=Swetha|title=A career in forgettable cameos: Here is FTII chairman Gajendra Chauhan's filmography|work=[[Firstpost]]|date=17 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Mahabharat ===\n{{Further|Mahabharat (1988 TV series)}}\nChauhan was initially offered to play the role of Lord [[Krishna]] in the television series, and shot for two episodes of the series in this role.<ref name=\"Times of India\">{{cite web|last1=Sharma|first1=Suruchi|title=I'm 600 series old now: Gajendra Chauhan|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/hindi/Im-600-serials-old-now-Gajendra-Chauhan/articleshow/11765192.cms|website=timesofindia.com|publisher=[[The Times of India]]|accessdate=12 July 2015|date=6 February 2012}}</ref> However filming for the first series was delayed, and Chauhan moved south to take on new work.<ref name=\"Times of India\"/> Upon his return, Chauhan had put on weight and was considered unsuitable for the role of Krishna. He was later offered the role of [[Yudhishthira]], which went on to being the role he has become better known by.<ref name=\"Times of India\"/>\n\n==Administration and politics==\nChauhan has also been involved in the administration of ''Cinema and Television Artists Association'' for 20 years, and served as its president for a year.<ref name=\"IE June 18, 2015\" /><ref name=\"rediff.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/yes-i-have-done-adult-films-but-nobody-is-talking-about-my-good-films/20150630.htm|title='Yes, I have done adult films. But nobody is talking about my good films'|date=30 June 2015|accessdate=12 July 2015|website=rediff.com|publisher=Rediff Movies}}</ref> In 2004 Chauhan entered politics,<ref name=indiatimes.com /> and became a member of the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] (BJP), for which he has worked as the national convener for culture.<ref name=\"IE June 18, 2015\" /><ref name=NDTV>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/protests-at-film-institute-in-pune-after-actor-bjp-member-gajendra-chauhan-is-appointed-chief-771313|title=Protests at Film Institute in Pune After Actor-BJP Member Gajendra Chauhan is Appointed Chief|date=13 June 2015|accessdate=12 July 2015|website=ndtv.com|publisher=NDTV}}</ref>\n\n===Chairman of Film and Television Institute of India===\n{{Further|Film and Television Institute of India}}\nOn 9 June 2015, Chauhan was appointed as the Chairman of the [[Film and Television Institute of India]] (FTII).<ref name=\"FTII appointment\">{{cite web|last1=Joshi|first1=Yogesh|title=Mahabharat actor as FTII prez sparks students' protest over BJP link|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/mumbai/ftii-students-say-protests-to-continue-against-appointment-of-new-chairperson/article1-1358025.aspx|website=hindustantimes.com|publisher=[[Hindustan Times]]|accessdate=12 July 2015|date=13 June 2015}}</ref> His appointment proved to be controversial amid allegations by students that it was a blatant attempt to \"[[saffronization|saffronize]] the institute\".<ref name=\"FTII appointment\"/> A section of left-wing students association, including [[All India Students Association]] (AISA) (the student wing of the [[Communist Party of India (Marxist\u2013Leninist) Liberation]]) continue to agitate.<ref name=AISA>{{cite web|author1=ANI|title=AISA protests against Gajendra Chauhan's appointment as FTII chief|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ani/aisa-protests-against-gajendra-chauhan-s-appointment-as-ftii-chief-115061600309_1.html|website=business-standard.com|publisher=Business Standard|accessdate=12 July 2015|date=16 June 2015}}</ref> Chauhan requested the students to give him a year to prove himself, and insisted that he would be better than the previous chairpersons.<ref name=\"anujkumar\">{{cite web|last1=Kumar|first1=Anij|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/i-am-a-self-made-man/article7329869.ece|title=I am a self-made man|website=thehindu.com|publisher=The Hundu|accessdate=12 July 2015|date=18 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nAmong those who have supported Chauhan's appointment as FTII chairman are BJP supporters and politicians including [[Mukesh Khanna]],<ref>http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/pune/Students-willing-for-talks-ministry-still-backs-choice/articleshow/48011905.cms</ref>[[Shatrughan Sinha]], [[Paresh Rawal]], [[Hema Malini]], [[Rajyavardhan Singh Rathore]], and [[Paintal]].<ref name=\"rediff.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Rajyavardhan Singh Rathore defends Gajendra Chauhan's selection as FTII chief|url=http://www.mid-day.com/articles/rajyavardhan-singh-rathore-defends-gajendra-chauhans-selection-as-ftii-chief/16361159|website=mid-day.com|publisher=Mid-Day|accessdate=12 July 2015|date=11 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author1=PTI|title=Gajendra Chauhan chosen over icons as he could devote more time|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/gajendra-chauhan-chosen-over-icons-as-he-could-devote-more-time-government/|website=indianexpress.com|publisher=Indian Express|accessdate=12 July 2015|date=10 July 2015}}</ref> Many more including FTII alumni and former teachers, actors, film technicians, filmmakers and political leaders have opposed his appointment, prominent among whom include [[Ranbir Kapoor]], [[Kalki Koechlin]], [[Nawazuddin Siddiqui]], [[Anupam Kher]], [[Piyush Mishra]], [[Anand Patwardhan]], [[Kiran Rao]], [[Jahnu Barua]], [[Salman Khan]], [[Rishi Kapoor]],<ref>{{cite web|title=FTII row: Top Bollywood personalities join chorus against Gajendra Chauhan|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/ftii-row-top-bollywood-personalities-join-chorus-against-gajendra-chauhan/1/450384.html|website=indiatoday.com|publisher=India Today|accessdate=12 July 2015|date=9 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Venugopal|first1=Vasudha|title=Amitabh Bachchan could've been FTII chairman, but Modi govt ignored I&B list and selected Gajendra Chauhan|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/amitabh-bachchan-couldve-been-ftii-chairman-but-modi-govt-ignored-ib-list-and-selected-gajendra-chauhan/articleshow/48025768.cms|website=economictimes.com|publisher=The Economic Times|accessdate=12 July 2015|date=11 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=It is nothing to be happy or dissatisfied about: Jahnu Barua on Gajendra Chauhan's appointment as FTII chairman|url=http://www.ibnlive.com/news/movies/giving-gajendra-chauhan-a-chance-is-not-a-problem-jahnu-barua-on-ftii-stir-1005896.html|website=ibnlive.com|publisher=IBN Live|accessdate=12 July 2015|date=14 June 2015}}</ref> [[Resul Pookutty]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/resul-pookutty-on-ftii-controversy-gajendra-chauhan-cannot-inspire-students-777502|title=Resul Pookutty on FTII Controversy: Gajendra Chauhan Cannot Inspire Students|date=2 July 2015|accessdate=6 August 2015|publisher=NDTV}}</ref> [[Rajkummar Rao]], [[Amol Palekar]],<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/ftii-row-rajkummar-rao-amol-palekar-demand-chauhan-s-removal-115071100436_1.html|title=Rajkummar Rao, Amol Palekar demand Chauhan\u2019s removal|date=11 July 2015|accessdate=6 August 2015|newspaper=Business Standard}}</ref> [[Soumitra Chatterjee]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/gajendra-chauhan-who-veteran-actor-soumitra-chatterjee-backs-ftii-protests-1203303|title='Gajendra Chauhan Who?': Veteran Actor Soumitra Chatterjee Backs FTII Protests|date=3 August 2015|accessdate=6 August 2015|publisher=NDTV}}</ref> [[Rahul Gandhi]] and [[Arvind Kejriwal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-ftii-row-after-salman-khan-and-rahul-gandhi-arvind-kejriwal-speaks-up-against-gajendra-chauhan-2111317|title=After Salman Khan and Rahul Gandhi, Arvind Kejriwal speaks up against Gajendra Chauhan|date=5 August 2015|accessdate=6 August 2015|publisher=DNA}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"|Year\n! scope=\"col\"|Title\n! scope=\"col\"|Role\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\" | 1985\n| ''Main Chup Nahi Rahungi''\n|\n|-\n| ''Lallu Ram''\n| Sub Inspector\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''Jungle Love''\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\" | 1989\n| ''[[Khuli Khidki]]''\n| Avinash\n|-\n| ''Awara Zindagi''\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\" | 1991\n| ''Vasna''\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Dancer (1991 film)|Dancer]]''\n| Joshi\n|-\n| ''Jungle Ki Rani''\n|\n|-\n| ''Naagmani''\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\" | 1992\n| ''Jungle Ka Beta''\n|\n|-\n| ''Jawani Janeman''\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Dilwale Kabhi Na Hare]]''\n| Shibu\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''Mulaquat'' \n| Balraj\n|-\n|rowspan=\"8\" | 1994\n| ''Watan''\n|\n|-\n| ''Jai Maa Vaishno Devi''\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Pathreela Raasta]]'' \n|\n|-\n| ''[[Janam Se Pehle]]'' \n|\n|-\n| ''[[Vaade Iraade]]''\n|\n|-\n| ''Mohini''\n| Gandharv\n|-\n| ''Sone Ki Sita''\n|\n|-\n| [[Aao Pyaar Karen (1994 film)|Aao Pyaar Karen]]\n| Suraj\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\" | 1995\n| ''[[Ham Sab Chor Hain (1995 film)|Hum Sab Chor Hain]]''\n| Police Commissioner\n|-\n| ''Kaala Sach''\n|\n|-\n|