{"title_page": "Rebecca Rippon", "text_new": "{{Use Australian English|date=March 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2012}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| headercolor    = \n| name           = Rebecca Rippon\n| image          = \n| image_size     = <!--Only for images narrower than 220 pixels.-->\n| caption        = \n| birth_name     = \n| fullname       = Rebecca Marie Rippon\n| nickname       = Beccy, Mike, 4 \n| nationality    = \n| residence      = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1978|12|26|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = <!-- {{convert|}} (yyyy) -->\n| weight         = <!-- {{convert|}} (yyyy) -->\n| website        = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} -->\n| country        = Australia\n| sport          = Water polo\n| event          = \n| collegeteam    = \n| club           = [[Cronulla Sharks Water Polo Club|Cronulla Water Polo Club]]\n| team           = \n| turnedpro      = \n| coach          = \n| retired        = 2012\n| coaching       = \n| worlds         = \n| regionals      = \n| nationals      = \n| olympics       = 2004 Summer, 2008 Summer\n| paralympics    = \n| highestranking = \n| pb             = \n|medaltemplates=\n{{MedalSport|Women's [[water polo]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{AUS}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Water polo at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2008 Summer Olympics|2008 China]]|[[Water polo at the 2008 Summer Olympics|Team competition]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|World Cup }}\n{{MedalGold|2006 World Cup|Team competition}}\n{{MedalCompetition|Pan Pacific Championships}}\n{{MedalGold|2012Pan Pacific|Team competition}}\n{{MedalCompetition|FINA World }}\n{{MedalSilver|2007 World Championships|Team competition}}\n}}\n\n'''Rebecca Marie Rippon''' (born 26 December 1978) is an Australian [[water polo]] player. She represented Australia as a member of the [[Australia women's national water polo team]] at the [[2004 Summer Olympics]] and the [[2008 Summer Olympics]], where she won a bronze medal.\n\n==Personal==\nRippon is from the Sydney area<ref name=not-chosen>{{cite web |url=http://wwos.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=8413984 |title=Rippon misses Australia's water polo squad |publisher=Wwos.ninemsn.com.au |accessdate=2012-02-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140318052814/http://wwos.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=8413984 |archivedate=18 March 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> of [[Chester Hill, New South Wales]].<ref name=poor-rippon>{{cite web|last=Herbertson |first=Lisa |url=http://express.whereilive.com.au/sport/story/shark-circles-australian-team-berth/ |title=Shark circles Australian team berth - Waterpolo - Sport - Canterbury-Bankstown Express |publisher=Express.whereilive.com.au |date=13 February 2012 |accessdate=2012-02-17}}</ref> Her nicknames include Beccy, Mike, and 4. She is {{convert|167|cm}} tall and weighs {{convert|72|kg}}.<ref name=sport-refer>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ri/rebecca-rippon-1.html |title=Bec Rippon Biography and Olympic Results &#124; Olympics at |publisher=Sports-reference.com |date= |accessdate=17 February 2012}}</ref> She has a sister, [[Melissa Rippon]], who also plays water polo for Australia's national water polo team.<ref name=\"not-chosen\"/> She has a step-sister [[Kate Gynther]], who also has represented Australia in water polo.<ref name=pan-pacific>{{cite news|title=London looms as a splash and grab job - - COUNTRY SPORT|newspaper=Sunday Telegraph|location=Sydney, Australia|date=1 January 2012|first=David|last=Packwood|page=073}}</ref> Her mother died in 2000 as a result of [[breast cancer]].<ref name=more-cuts2>{{cite news|title=Stinger survivors in the swim for third Olympics|first=Jon|last=Tuxworth|newspaper=Canberra Times|location=Canberra, Australian Capital Territory|page=19|date=21 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Water polo==\nRippon's home competition pool is [[Sutherland Leisure Centre]].<ref name=retired>{{cite web |last=Forrest |first=Brad |url=http://www.theleader.com.au/news/local/sport/waterpolo/push-to-get-star-in-the-pool/2441948.aspx |title=Push to get star in the pool - Local News - Sport - Waterpolo - St George & Sutherland Shire Leader |publisher=Theleader.com.au |date=5 February 2012 |accessdate=2012-02-17}} {{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}</ref>\n\n===Club===\nRippon played club water polo for [[Cronulla Sharks Water Polo Club|Cronulla Water Polo Club]] in the [[Australian National Water Polo League|National Water Polo League]], until her 2012 retirement from the sport.<ref name=\"retired\"/> She was a member of the team in 2011.<ref name=sharks-2011>{{cite news|title=Sharks lose in shootout heartbreaker|newspaper=St. George and Sutherland Shire Leader|location=New South Wales, Australia|date=9 May 2011|id=2158629|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AUNB:SGAS&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=137270A4E8260F98&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=1053B823C33F21F9}}</ref> Her team tried to encourage her to change her mind into the second month of the season.<ref name=take-break>{{cite news|title=Forrest Fires: Water polo side tries to stay afloat|newspaper=St. George and Sutherland Shire Leader|location=New South Wales, Australia|date=16 February 2012|first=Brad|last=Forrest|id=2458211|accessdate=18 February 2012|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid}}</ref> The campaign to get her to return was led by her Serbian born coach [[Predrag Mihailovic]].<ref name=serbian-born>{{cite news|title=Push to get star in the pool|newspaper=St. George and Sutherland Shire Leader|location=New South Wales, Australia|date=4 February 2012|first=Brad|last=Forrest|id=2441948|accessdate=17 February 2012|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AUNB:SGAS&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=13CAC2226D62FCF0&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=1053B823C33F21F9}}</ref> She has also played for [[Balmain Water Polo Club]] in 2008 and 2010 in the National Water Polo League.<ref name=\"sport-refer\"/><ref name=missed-season>{{cite news|title=Cronulla power through to finals series|newspaper=St. George and Sutherland Shire Leader|location=New South Wales, Australia|date=3 May 2011|first=Brad|last=Forrest|id=2151588|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AUNB:SGAS&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=137021F85F2C5CA8&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=1053B823C33F21F9}}</ref><ref name=qld-polo>{{cite web|url=http://www.canberratimes.com.au/sport/australian-womens-water-polo-team-named-20080512-2d63.html |title=Australian women's water polo team named |publisher=Canberratimes.com.au |date=12 May 2008 |accessdate=2012-02-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140710142437/http://www.canberratimes.com.au/sport/australian-womens-water-polo-team-named-20080512-2d63.html |archivedate=10 July 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, she played club water polo in Greece for [[Vouliagmeni Nautical Club]] and for the [[Balmain Tigers]] in the National Water Polo League.<ref name=first-gold>{{cite web|last=Heaney |first=Claire |url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/news/underwater-warfare/story-e6frer7x-1111113037905 |title=Underwater warfare |publisher=The Courier-Mail |date=23 February 2007 |accessdate=2012-02-22}}</ref>\n\n===National team===\nRippon has made 265 appearances for the Australian national team.<ref name=\"not-chosen\"/> She won gold medals at a member of the national team at the 2006 World Cup and 2012 Pan Pacific. She won a silver medal at the 2007 World Championships.<ref name=\"not-chosen\"/> She was named to the team that competed in 2008 at the FINA world league preliminary round in Tianjin, China.<ref name=\"qld-polo\" /> In a 2008 Asia-Oceania qualifier against China for the World League Super Finals, she played in the 11-9 win that went to a penalty shoot out. In the match, she scored a goal for Australia.<ref name=beat-china>{{cite web|url=http://www.canberratimes.com.au/sport/stingers-beat-china-in-preolympic-game-20080522-2h26.html |title=Stingers beat China in pre-Olympic game |publisher=Canberratimes.com.au |date=22 May 2008 |accessdate=2012-02-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140409054320/http://www.canberratimes.com.au/sport/stingers-beat-china-in-preolympic-game-20080522-2h26.html |archivedate= 9 April 2014}}</ref> In 2009, she was a member of a team that compete at the FINA World Championships. She played in the semi-finals game against New Zealand that Australia won 14-4. In the game, she scored three goals.<ref name=new-zealand-win>{{cite web|last=Jeffery |first=Nicole |url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/mitcham-pushes-the-enevelope/story-e6frecj3-1225754240015 |title=Mitcham pushes the enevelope |publisher=The Courier-Mail |date=24 July 2009 |accessdate=2012-02-22}}</ref> After being cut from the national team competing at the [[2012 Summer Olympics]], she announced her retirement from the sport.<ref name=\"retired\" /> In April 2011, she attended a training camp at the [[Australian Institute of Sport]] where the coach was \"selecting a team for the major championships over winter.\"<ref name=chose-team-camp>{{cite news|title=Canberra Times: Aussies hoping to bring US down|newspaper=Canberra Times|location=Canberra, Australia|date=20 April 2011|publisher=Financial Times Limited - Asia Africa Intelligence Wire|id=WCTS86960225|accessdate=18 February 2012|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AUNB:ATMB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=136B9B765282E440&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=1053B823C33F21F9}}</ref> In July 2011, she was a member of the Australian Stingers that competed in the 2011 FINA World Championships in Shanghai as a field player.<ref name=china-game>{{cite news|title=Canberra Times: SCOREBOARD|newspaper=Canberra Times|location=Canberra, Australia|date=6 July 2011|publisher=Financial Times Limited - Asia Africa Intelligence Wire|id=WCTS88924540}}</ref> In preparation for this tournament, she attended a team training camp in [[Perth, Western Australia]].<ref name=training-camp2>{{cite news|title=AAP News: WPOL:Stingers squad named for worlds|newspaper=AAP News|location=Australia|date=5 July 2011|publisher=Financial Times Limited - Asia Africa Intelligence Wire|id=WAAP88910998}}</ref> She competed in the [[Pan Pacific Water Polo Championships|Pan Pacific Championships]] in January 2012 for the Australian Stingers.<ref name=\"pan-pacific\"/>\n\n===Olympics===\nRippon competed at the [[2004 Summer Olympics]] and the [[2008 Summer Olympics]] on the [[Australia women's national water polo team]].<ref name=\"not-chosen\"/><ref name=\"sport-refer\"/> She scored a goal late in the Bronze medal match against Hungary that helped her team win.<ref name=\"not-chosen\" /> She was not chosen to compete at the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] in London.<ref name=\"not-chosen\"/><ref name=\"poor-rippon\"/><ref name=more-cuts>{{cite web|url=http://au.ibtimes.com/articles/293300/20120206/final-aussie-stingers-olympic-train-squad-announced.htm |title=Final Aussie Stingers Olympic train on Squad Announced |publisher=Au.ibtimes.com |date=6 February 2012 |accessdate=2012-02-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140314014813/http://au.ibtimes.com/articles/293300/20120206/final-aussie-stingers-olympic-train-squad-announced.htm |archivedate=14 March 2014 }}</ref><ref name=cut-3>{{cite web |author=The two-time Olympian will not feature at the 2012 Games |url=http://www1.skysports.com/olympics/story/21837/7501320 |title=Rippon misses out &#124; Water Polo &#124; London 2012 &#124; Sky Sports Olympics |publisher=.skysports.com |accessdate=2012-02-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130104154715/http://www1.skysports.com/olympics/story/21837/7501320 |archivedate=4 January 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> She was one of the last two players, alongside [[Lea Barta]], before the final team for London was announced.<ref name=\"more-cuts\"/> Prior to Rebecca Rippon being cut from the 2012 Olympic squad, .<ref name=\"not-chosen\"/><ref name=\"poor-rippon\"/><ref name=\"more-cuts\"/><ref name=\"cut-3\"/> sisters Kate Gynther, Melissa Rippon and Rebecca Rippon had hoped to become the first set of Australian siblings to all compete at three consecutive [[Olympic Games]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Tuxworth|first=Jon|title=Stinger survivors in the swim for third Olympics|url=http://www.canberratimes.com.au/sport/stinger-survivors-in-the-swim-for-third-olympics-20120220-1tk1y.html|accessdate=5 March 2012|newspaper=Canberra Times|date=21 February 2012|location=Canberra AU}}</ref><ref name=set-record-sad>{{cite news|title=London looms as a splash and grab job - - COUNTRY SPORT|newspaper=Sunday Telegraph|location=Sydney, Australia|date=1 January 2012|first=David|last=Packwood|page=73}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n{{Australia Women Water Polo Squad 2008 Summer Olympics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rippon, Rebecca}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian female water polo players]]\n[[Category:Olympic water polo players of Australia]]\n[[Category:Water polo players at the 2004 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Water polo players at the 2008 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic bronze medalists for Australia]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in water polo]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2008 Summer Olympics]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Australian English|date=March 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2012}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| headercolor    = \n| name           = Rebecca Rippon\n| image          = \n| image_size     = <!--Only for images narrower than 220 pixels.-->\n| caption        = \n| birth_name     = \n| fullname       = Rebecca Marie Rippon\n| nickname       = Beccy, Mike, 4 \n| nationality    = \n| residence      = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1978|12|26|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = <!-- {{convert|}} (yyyy) -->\n| weight         = <!-- {{convert|}} (yyyy) -->\n| website        = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} -->\n| country        = Australia\n| sport          = Water polo\n| event          = \n| collegeteam    = \n| club           = [[Cronulla Sharks Water Polo Club|Cronulla Water Polo Club]]\n| team           = \n| turnedpro      = \n| coach          = \n| retired        = 2012\n| coaching       = \n| worlds         = \n| regionals      = \n| nationals      = \n| olympics       = 2004 Summer, 2008 Summer\n| paralympics    = \n| highestranking = \n| pb             = \n|medaltemplates=\n{{MedalSport|Women's [[water polo]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{AUS}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Water polo at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2008 Summer Olympics|2008 China]]|[[Water polo at the 2008 Summer Olympics|Team competition]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|World Cup }}\n{{MedalGold|2006 World Cup|Team competition}}\n{{MedalCompetition|Pan Pacific Championships}}\n{{MedalGold|2012Pan Pacific|Team competition}}\n{{MedalCompetition|FINA World }}\n{{MedalSilver|2007 World Championships|Team competition}}\n}}\n\n'''Rebecca Marie Rippon''' (born 26 December 1978) is an Australian [[water polo]] player.  She represented Australia as a member of the [[Australia women's national water polo team]] at the [[2004 Summer Olympics]] and the [[2008 Summer Olympics]], where she won a bronze medal.\n\n==Personal==\nRippon is from the Sydney area<ref name=not-chosen>{{cite web |url=http://wwos.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=8413984 |title=Rippon misses Australia's water polo squad |publisher=Wwos.ninemsn.com.au |accessdate=2012-02-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140318052814/http://wwos.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=8413984 |archivedate=18 March 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> of [[Chester Hill, New South Wales]].<ref name=poor-rippon>{{cite web|last=Herbertson |first=Lisa |url=http://express.whereilive.com.au/sport/story/shark-circles-australian-team-berth/ |title=Shark circles Australian team berth - Waterpolo - Sport - Canterbury-Bankstown Express |publisher=Express.whereilive.com.au |date=13 February 2012 |accessdate=2012-02-17}}</ref>   Her nicknames include Beccy, Mike, and 4.  She is {{convert|167|cm}} tall and weighs {{convert|72|kg}}.<ref name=sport-refer>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ri/rebecca-rippon-1.html |title=Bec Rippon Biography and Olympic Results &#124; Olympics at |publisher=Sports-reference.com |date= |accessdate=17 February 2012}}</ref> She has a sister, [[Melissa Rippon]], who also plays water polo for Australia's national water polo team.<ref name=\"not-chosen\"/> She has a step-sister [[Kate Gynther]], who also has represented Australia in water polo.<ref name=pan-pacific>{{cite news|title=London looms as a splash and grab job - - COUNTRY SPORT|newspaper=Sunday Telegraph|location=Sydney, Australia|date=1 January 2012|first=David|last=Packwood|page=073}}</ref> Her mother died in 2000 as a result of [[breast cancer]].<ref name=more-cuts>{{cite news|title=Stinger survivors in the swim for third Olympics|first=Jon|last=Tuxworth|newspaper=Canberra Times|location=Canberra, Australian Capital Territory|page=19|date=21 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Water polo==\nRippon's home competition pool is [[Sutherland Leisure Centre]].<ref name=retired>{{cite web |last=Forrest |first=Brad |url=http://www.theleader.com.au/news/local/sport/waterpolo/push-to-get-star-in-the-pool/2441948.aspx |title=Push to get star in the pool - Local News - Sport - Waterpolo - St George & Sutherland Shire Leader |publisher=Theleader.com.au |date=5 February 2012 |accessdate=2012-02-17 }}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===Club===\nRippon played club water polo for [[Cronulla Sharks Water Polo Club|Cronulla Water Polo Club]] in the [[Australian National Water Polo League|National Water Polo League]], until her 2012 retirement from the sport.<ref name=\"retired\"/> She was a member of the team in 2011.<ref name=sharks-2011>{{cite news|title=Sharks lose in shootout heartbreaker|newspaper=St. George and Sutherland Shire Leader|location=New South Wales, Australia|date=9 May 2011|id=2158629|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AUNB:SGAS&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=137270A4E8260F98&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=1053B823C33F21F9}}</ref>  Her team tried to encourage her to change her mind into the second month of the season.<ref name=take-break>{{cite news|title=Forrest Fires: Water polo side tries to stay afloat|newspaper=St. George and Sutherland Shire Leader|location=New South Wales, Australia|date=16 February 2012|first=Brad|last=Forrest|id=2458211|accessdate=18 February 2012|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid}}</ref> The campaign to get her to return was led by her Serbian born coach [[Predrag Mihailovic]].<ref name=serbian-born>{{cite news|title=Push to get star in the pool|newspaper=St. George and Sutherland Shire Leader|location=New South Wales, Australia|date=4 February 2012|first=Brad|last=Forrest|id=2441948|accessdate=17 February 2012|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AUNB:SGAS&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=13CAC2226D62FCF0&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=1053B823C33F21F9}}</ref> She has also played for [[Balmain Water Polo Club]] in 2008 and 2010 in the National Water Polo League.<ref name=\"sport-refer\"/><ref name=missed-season>{{cite news|title=Cronulla power through to finals series|newspaper=St. George and Sutherland Shire Leader|location=New South Wales, Australia|date=3 May 2011|first=Brad|last=Forrest|id=2151588|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AUNB:SGAS&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=137021F85F2C5CA8&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=1053B823C33F21F9}}</ref><ref name=qld-polo>{{cite web|url=http://www.canberratimes.com.au/sport/australian-womens-water-polo-team-named-20080512-2d63.html |title=Australian women's water polo team named |publisher=Canberratimes.com.au |date=12 May 2008 |accessdate=2012-02-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140710142437/http://www.canberratimes.com.au/sport/australian-womens-water-polo-team-named-20080512-2d63.html |archivedate=10 July 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, she played club water polo in Greece for [[Vouliagmeni Nautical Club]] and for the [[Balmain Tigers]] in the National Water Polo League.<ref name=first-gold>{{cite web|last=Heaney |first=Claire |url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/news/underwater-warfare/story-e6frer7x-1111113037905 |title=Underwater warfare |publisher=The Courier-Mail |date=23 February 2007 |accessdate=2012-02-22}}</ref>\n\n===National team===\nRippon has made 265 appearances for the Australian national team.<ref name=\"not-chosen\"/> She won gold medals at a member of the national team at the 2006 World Cup and 2012 Pan Pacific.  She won a silver medal at the 2007 World Championships.<ref name=\"not-chosen\"/> She was named to the team that competed in 2008 at the FINA world league preliminary round in Tianjin, China.<ref name=\"qld-polo\"/>  In a 2008 Asia-Oceania qualifier against China for the World League Super Finals, she played in the 11-9 win that went to a penalty shoot out.  In the match, she scored a goal for Australia.<ref name=beat-china>{{cite web|url=http://www.canberratimes.com.au/sport/stingers-beat-china-in-preolympic-game-20080522-2h26.html |title=Stingers beat China in pre-Olympic game |publisher=Canberratimes.com.au |date=22 May 2008 |accessdate=2012-02-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140409054320/http://www.canberratimes.com.au/sport/stingers-beat-china-in-preolympic-game-20080522-2h26.html |archivedate= 9 April 2014 }}</ref>  In 2009, she was a member of a team that compete at the FINA World Championships.  She played in the semi-finals game against New Zealand that Australia won 14-4.  In the game, she scored three goals.<ref name=new-zealand-win>{{cite web|last=Jeffery |first=Nicole |url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/mitcham-pushes-the-enevelope/story-e6frecj3-1225754240015 |title=Mitcham pushes the enevelope |publisher=The Courier-Mail |date=24 July 2009 |accessdate=2012-02-22}}</ref> After being cut from the national team competing at the [[2012 Summer Olympics]], she announced her retirement from the sport.<ref name=\"retired\"/>  In April 2011, she attended a training camp at the [[Australian Institute of Sport]] where the coach was \"selecting a team for the major championships over winter.\"<ref name=chose-team-camp>{{cite news|title=Canberra Times: Aussies hoping to bring US down|newspaper=Canberra Times|location=Canberra, Australia|date=20 April 2011|publisher=Financial Times Limited - Asia Africa Intelligence Wire|id=WCTS86960225|accessdate=18 February 2012|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AUNB:ATMB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=136B9B765282E440&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=1053B823C33F21F9}}</ref> In July 2011, she was a member of the Australian Stingers that competed in the 2011 FINA World Championships in Shanghai as a field player.<ref name=china-game>{{cite news|title=Canberra Times: SCOREBOARD|newspaper=Canberra Times|location=Canberra, Australia|date=6 July 2011|publisher=Financial Times Limited - Asia Africa Intelligence Wire|id=WCTS88924540}}</ref> In preparation for this tournament, she attended a team training camp in [[Perth, Western Australia]].<ref name=training-camp2>{{cite news|title=AAP News: WPOL:Stingers squad named for worlds|newspaper=AAP News|location=Australia|date=5 July 2011|publisher=Financial Times Limited - Asia Africa Intelligence Wire|id=WAAP88910998}}</ref> She competed in the [[Pan Pacific Water Polo Championships|Pan Pacific Championships]] in January 2012 for the Australian Stingers.<ref name=\"pan-pacific\"/>\n\n===Olympics===\nRippon competed at the [[2004 Summer Olympics]] and the [[2008 Summer Olympics]] on the [[Australia women's national water polo team]].<ref name=\"not-chosen\"/><ref name=\"sport-refer\"/> She scored a goal late in the Bronze medal match against Hungary that helped her team win.<ref name=\"not-chosen\"/>  She was not chosen to compete at the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] in London.<ref name=\"not-chosen\"/><ref name=\"poor-rippon\"/><ref name=more-cuts>{{cite web|url=http://au.ibtimes.com/articles/293300/20120206/final-aussie-stingers-olympic-train-squad-announced.htm |title=Final Aussie Stingers Olympic train on Squad Announced |publisher=Au.ibtimes.com |date=6 February 2012 |accessdate=2012-02-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140314014813/http://au.ibtimes.com/articles/293300/20120206/final-aussie-stingers-olympic-train-squad-announced.htm |archivedate=14 March 2014 }}</ref><ref name=cut-3>{{cite web |author=The two-time Olympian will not feature at the 2012 Games |url=http://www1.skysports.com/olympics/story/21837/7501320 |title=Rippon misses out &#124; Water Polo &#124; London 2012 &#124; Sky Sports Olympics |publisher=.skysports.com |accessdate=2012-02-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130104154715/http://www1.skysports.com/olympics/story/21837/7501320 |archivedate=4 January 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> She was one of the last two players, alongside [[Lea Barta]], before the final team for London was announced.<ref name=\"more-cuts\"/> Prior to Rebecca Rippon being cut from the 2012 Olympic squad, .<ref name=\"not-chosen\"/><ref name=\"poor-rippon\"/><ref name=\"more-cuts\"/><ref name=\"cut-3\"/> sisters Kate Gynther, Melissa Rippon and Rebecca Rippon had hoped to become the first set of Australian siblings to all compete at three consecutive [[Olympic Games]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Tuxworth|first=Jon|title=Stinger survivors in the swim for third Olympics|url=http://www.canberratimes.com.au/sport/stinger-survivors-in-the-swim-for-third-olympics-20120220-1tk1y.html|accessdate=5 March 2012|newspaper=Canberra Times|date=21 February 2012|location=Canberra AU}}</ref><ref name=set-record-sad>{{cite news|title=London looms as a splash and grab job - - COUNTRY SPORT|newspaper=Sunday Telegraph|location=Sydney, Australia|date=1 January 2012|first=David|last=Packwood|page=73}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n{{Australia Women Water Polo Squad 2008 Summer Olympics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rippon, Rebecca}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian female water polo players]]\n[[Category:Olympic water polo players of Australia]]\n[[Category:Water polo players at the 2004 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Water polo players at the 2008 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic bronze medalists for Australia]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in water polo]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2008 Summer Olympics]]\n", "name_user": "Quebec99", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix duplicate ref names \u2013You can help!", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rebecca_Rippon"}
{"title_page": "Staci Keanan", "text_new": "{{short description|American attorney and Actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name            = Stacy Keanan\n| image           = \n| caption         = \n| birthname       = Anastasia Love Sagorsky\n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1975|06|06|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place     = [[Devon, Pennsylvania]], US\n| other_names     = {{Plainlist|\n* Anastasia Sagorsky\n* Staci Keanan\n* Anastasia Birtwhistle\n}}\n| alma_mater      = [[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]]<br>[[Southwestern Law School]]\n| occupation      = Actress (1987\u20132010)<br>Attorney (2013\u2013present)\n| spouse          = {{marriage|Guy Birtwhistle|2017|}}\n}}\n\n'''Stacy Keanan''' (born '''Anastasia Love Sagorsky''' on June 6, 1975)<ref name=\"filmref\">{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/21/Staci-Keanan.html|title=Staci Keanan Biography (1975-)|website=Filmreference.com|accessdate=March 7, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"Calbar\">{{cite web|title=The State Bar of California: Attorney Search|url=http://members.calbar.ca.gov/fal/member/detail/292053|website=calbar.ca.gov|publisher=The State Bar of California|accessdate=January 1, 2018}}</ref> is an American [[deputy district attorney]] and former [[actor|actress]]. Keanan is best known for portraying the role of Nicole Bradford on the [[NBC]] sitcom ''[[My Two Dads]]'', from 1987 to 1990, and as Dana Foster on the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]/[[CBS]] sitcom ''[[Step by Step (TV series)|Step by Step]]'', from 1991 to 1998.\n\n==Early life==\nKeanan was born in [[Devon, Pennsylvania]] (near [[Philadelphia]]), the daughter of Jacqueline (n\u00e9e Love) and Irv Sagorsky, a car salesman.<ref name=filmref/><ref name=\"likes having\">Kim, Jae-Ha. [http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=CSTB&p_theme=cstb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB36E8867362019&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM \"Actress likes having '2 Dads'\"], ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'', November 17, 1989.</ref><ref name=\"J obit\">[http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=PI&s_site=philly&p_multi=PI&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=129CE5D9BA75BE78&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM Obituary for Jacqueline Love Sagorsky], ''[[Philadelphia Inquirer]]'', July 30, 2009.</ref> She has a sister, Pilar.<ref name=\"J obit\" /> \n\n==Career==\n===Acting===\nAt age five, she began modeling and appeared in print, radio, and television advertisements, including the voice of [[My Little Pony]] and television commercials for [[Burger King]] and [[Hershey's Kisses]]. As a youth, Keenan moved with her mother and sister to [[New York City]], where she changed her name to \"Staci Love\" and began appearing in [[summer stock theatre|summer stock]]. She made her credited television debut in the 1987 miniseries ''[[I'll Take Manhattan (miniseries)|''I'll Take Manhattan]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20097658,00.html|title=For Staci Keanan of TV's My Two Dads, Hollywood Can Be a Two-Faced Town |last1=Blessing|first1=Angela |last2=Holmstrom|first2=Rick |date=November 23, 1987 |work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |accessdate=September 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAt the age of 12, shortly after she moved with her family to [[Los Angeles]], she was cast as Nicole Bradford in the TV series ''[[My Two Dads]]''. The series ran from 1987 to 1990. During the 1990-91 season, she co-starred in the short-lived series ''[[Going Places (U.S. TV series)|Going Places]]'' with [[Alan Ruck]], [[Heather Locklear]], and [[Hallie Todd]]. The following year, Keenan was cast as Dana Foster in the TV series ''[[Step by Step (TV series)|Step by Step]]'' which aired from 1991 to 1998. By 1997 Keenan had changed her name from ''Staci'' to ''Stacy.''<ref>Podcast: [http://blog.wtfthepodcast.com/2008/02/10/wtf-the-podcast-cont-again.aspx 'Keanan, Stacy. Interview with Brian Castro.']{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} ''from'' [4:24\"], ''IMDB listing misspelled''. WTF? the Podcast. FX Show, Orlando. January 2008. Retrieved on October 24, 2010.</ref>\n\nKeenan had roles in the short ''Stolen Poem'' (2004) and the films ''Hidden Secrets'' (2006), and ''Death and Cremation'' (2010) with [[Brad Dourif]], [[Jeremy Sumpter]], and [[Daniel Baldwin]]. In 2009 Keanan appeared in ''Holyman Undercover'',<ref name=filmref /> and in 2010 she appeared in a cameo in ''[[You Again]]'' with ''Step By Step'' castmates [[Christine Lakin]] and [[Patrick Duffy]]. She also co-starred in the 2009 film ''Sarah's Choice''.\n\n===Law===\nKeenan received her undergraduate degree from [[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]]. She then attended [[Southwestern Law School]] and was admitted to the [[State Bar of California]] in 2013. She currently practices law under her given name, Anastasia Sagorsky, in the Los Angeles area.<ref name=\"Calbar\" /> In 2014, Keenan worked as a prosecutor in the [[Riverside County, California|Riverside County]] District Attorney's Office who handles felony cases involving violent crime or death.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.riversidecountybar.com/Documents/Magazine-2014/Riverside-Lawyer-Magazine-volume-64-5-May-2014.pdf |title=The Inland Empire\u2013Southwestern Law School Connection |magazine=Riverside Lawyer |date=May 2014 |page=14}}</ref> By 2019, Keenan became a Deputy District Attorney in the [[Los Angeles County District Attorney]]'s office.<ref>{{cite new |url=http://da.lacounty.gov/media/news/man-sentenced-killing-77-year-old-woman-hit-and-run |title=Man Sentenced for Killing 77-Year-Old Woman in Hit-and-Run |work=Los Angeles County District Attorney's Office |date=August 16, 2019 |first=Paul |last=Eakins}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nOn February 11, 2017, Keenan married actor and producer Guy Birtwhistle.<ref>{{cite web|title='My Two Dads' Star Staci Keanan: Where Is She Now?|url=http://extratv.com/2014/08/23/my-two-dads-star-staci-keanan-where-is-she-now/|website=Extra|publisher=[[Extra (U.S. TV program)|Extra]]|accessdate=November 13, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Film roles\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Role\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1990\n| ''[[Lisa (1990 film)|Lisa]]''\n| Lisa\n| Alternative title: ''Candlelight Killer''\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''Skooled''\n|\n| Short film\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''Ski Hard''\n| Annie Meyers\n| Alternative titles: ''Downhill Willie'', ''Ski Nuts''\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''The Red Coat''\n| Mary\n| Short film\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''[[Nowhere (film)|Nowhere]]''\n| Ever\n| Credited as Stacy Keanan<ref>Film clip: [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=C4amsKBgLv8 'FILM \"NOWHERE\" CAST (1997)'] ''onscreen credits'' [1.43\"-1.47\"] ''as \"Stacy Keanan\".''</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/19970606235453/http://www.flf.com/nowhere/castcrew/index.html Nowhere (1997)] ''Cast and Crew'' at FLF.com (circa 1997 via [[Wayback Machine]].) Retrieved November 26, 2010.</ref>\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''Stolen Poem''\n| Jamie\nCredited as Stacy Keanan\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''Hidden Secrets''\n| Rachel Wilson\n| Credited as Stacy Keanan\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Sarah's Choice]]''\n| Denise\n| Credited as Stacy Keanan<ref>[[:File:Sarah's Choice.jpg|''Sarah\u2019s Choice DVD cover'']] ''DVD cover image''  Wikipedia.org. Retrieved October 24, 2010.</ref>\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Holyman Undercover]]''\n| Carmen\n| Credited as Stacy Keanan\n\n\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[You Again]]''\n| Dana\n| Credited as Stacy Keanan\n| \n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Death and Cremation]]''\n| Becky Weaver\n|Credited as Stacy Keanan \n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Television roles\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Role\n! scope=\"col\" class=